entry.title: Avoid memcpy(NULL) and memset(NULL) in base/pickle.cc
entry.content:
There is a specification bug in C, such that NULL, 0 may not be passed

to functions like memcpy or memset, despite it being a natural

representation of the empty slice. Although C++ broadly accepts NULL, 0

as the empty slice (a default constructed std::vector or std::span has

null data), it inherits this language bug from C.



Clang will not miscompile code based on this language bug, but it will

flag it in UBSan. And GCC will indeed miscompile based on this.

Hopefully [0] will be successful in trying to get this language bug

fixed. In the meantime, we should avoid tripping this.



The most straightforward way to avoid it is to condition memcpy and

memset on len != 0, but this is tedious. Instead, just use std::copy and

std::fill from . Those are defined to allow (null, 0).



[0] https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/49459#issuecomment-1753382089

entry.title: Dep on make_platform_generated in blink_headers
entry.content:
Make it safe (safer) to include headers from blink_headers when a target

only deps on //third_party/blink/public:blink_headers.



The blink_header target lists a large amount of blink headers, some of

which include generated headers. Without a proper dependency path to

the generators, the build is flaky and, for example, most of

//components/webcrypto could fail to build in a clean build with:

In file included from ../../components/webcrypto/status.cc:5:

In file included from ../../components/webcrypto/status.h:13:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/public/platform/web_crypto.h:36:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/public/platform/web_crypto_algorithm.h:35:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/public/platform/web_private_ptr.h:36:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/platform/heap/cross_thread_persistent.h:8:

../../third_party/blink/renderer/platform/heap/persistent.h:8:10: fatal error:

'third_party/blink/renderer/platform/heap/heap_buildflags.h' file not found



Fix by having blink_headers dep on make_platform_generated, which can be

extended to include more generated headers that blink_headers require.

This is blink_heap_buildflags currently.



Note that blink_platform_public_deps can't be used for this, because

that deps on blink_headers, so it'd be a cycle to also dep the other

way.



This fixes over 30 flaky build steps in the compilation of content_shell

alone. Other than webcrypto, those were:

obj/content/child/child/blink_platform_impl.o

obj/content/child/child/image_decoder_utils.o

obj/third_party/blink/renderer/platform/image-decoders/image_decoders/image_decoder.o

entry.title: ProfileTokenQuality resetting for legacy sync
entry.content:
ProfileTokenQuality observations are not synced for

AUTOFILL_PROFILE. Consequently, because AutofillTable implements updates

as remove + insert, whenever updates for a profile through

AUTOFILL_PROFILE Sync arrive, all existing observations for that profile

are dropped.



This CL adds logic that ensures that only observations for tokens those

values have changed are reset by incoming updates. E.g. if only the

first name is updated through AUTOFILL_PROFILE Sync, local observations

for the last name can be kept.



This is done by adapting AutofillProfile::OverwriteDataFrom(), a

function that already implements similar logic for other aspects of the

data model. More specifically, this CL:

- Renames AutofillProfile::OverwriteDataFrom() to

OverwriteDataFromForLegacySync(), since this is the only use case.

- Adds logic in OverwriteDataFromForLegacySync() that retains

observations for tokens those values haven't changed.



Since this is very similar to the resetting logic added for changes from

within Autofill in crrev.com/c/4905130, this logic is consolidate into

ProfileTokenQuality::ResetObservationsForDifferingTokens().



Bug: 1453650

entry.title: [@scope] Maintain "triggered scopes" on ElementRareData
entry.content:
This CL adds a new field StyleScopeData to ElementRareData,

which contains the implicit @scope rules that would be "triggered"

by having the corresponding Element on the stack during style recalc.



The purpose of this is to be able to go through an Element's ancestor

chain, and for each ancestor quickly determine if a given StyleScope

should be activated or not. The reason why this can be an expensive

check currently, is that a single StyleScope instance can refer to

any number of owning CSSStyleSheets (due to style sharing).

So for each ancestor, checking if a StyleScope applies is linear in

the number of identical CSSStyleSheets found elsewhere in the document.



This CL does not yet build any optimizations on top of StyleScopeData,

and the code is generally unused except for tests.



Note that ScopedStyleResolver now stores an ActiveStyleSheetVector

instead of a vector of CSSStyleSheets. This is needed because we

need to access the original RuleSets (from AppendActiveStyleSheets)

during ResetStyle. The RuleSets held by the CSSStyleSheets may have

been modified (or cleared) between AppendActiveStyleSheets and

ResetStyle, so we can't just grab Contents()->GetRuleSet() at that

time. Arguably, doing Contents()->GetRuleSet() is wrong anywhere in

ScopedStyleResolver, since we're not using the RuleSet instances we

were told to use by by AppendActiveStyleSheets.

entry.title: [//media] Disable 1c VideoFrame->GL upload for pure software VideoFrames
entry.content:
It is not possible to support pure software VideoFrames via our

MultiplanarSharedImage-based 1-copy VideoFrame->GL upload

implementation, as it is not possible to create a MultiplanarSharedImage

for such VideoFrames. These VideoFrames have format I420, and it is not

possible across all platforms to upload the VideoFrame's data via raster

to a MultiplanarSI with format I420 that is accessible by WebGL. Such an

SI must be backed by a native buffer to be accessible to WebGL, and

native buffer-backed I420 SharedImages are in general not supported (and

*cannot* be supported on Windows). 1-copy of pure software VideoFrames

*is* supported in the legacy 1-copy implementation that uses legacy

mailboxes to perform the copy. Hence, this support is a blocker in our

process of eliminating the legacy mailbox-based 1-copy implementation.



Whether 1 GPU-GPU copy or 2 GPU-GPU copies are performed for pure video

software VideoFrame upload to GL should not be a significant factor in

performance, as the dominant factor in terms of performance will be the

fact that the VideoFrame's data needs to be uploaded from the CPU to

the GPU. This CL disables 1-copy upload for pure software VideoFrames,

causing them to fall back to the two GPU-GPU copy path. We add a

base::Feature to serve as a reverse-killswitch while we roll out this

disabling.

entry.title: Only allow SMILTimeContainer auto-suspend for continuous anim. frames
entry.content:
When new elements are added to the timecontainer or an existing one gets

new interval, a timer will be set to update the timed elements based on

this new state. This request can also be picked up by the regular frame

update if it occurs before the timer fires. If the state synchronization

takes place when the timeline has not been updated for >=60s (== the lag

limit) the auto-suspend mechanism would trigger and apply the auto-

suspend behavior, causing a delay of animations.



Only allow the auto-suspend behavior to trigger on continuous animation

frame updates by checking what frame scheduling state the time container

was in when the animation frame was triggered. This matches the behavior

that the timer actually firing would yield (i.e WakeupTimerFired).

entry.title: [Android DevX] Fix/improve lldb script
entry.content:
The main fix here is to use spaces instead of gdb-style colons as the

separators for shared library paths in SOLIB_DIRS, passed on later in

"settings append target.exec-search-paths". This makes lldb actually use

all the pulled libraries, fixing it in arm32 where it was unable to get

any meaningful backtraces for me, and making it better on arm64 where

it would previously only see symbols from the Chromium build.



Also:

* Fix architecture detection: use correct variable in get_gn_target_arch

and add a case to catch what my "file" command reports for an Android

Arm64 build (... ELF 64-bit LSB shared object, ARM aarch64, ...).

* Add an alternative method of detecting APP_DATA_DIR if run-as doesn't

work (on a rooted device run-as may fail but we'll still be able to

run lldb).

* Add a --process-name switch to control what PID we'll grep for. This

is useful when attaching to something other than the main (browser)

process, avoids having to manually look for a pid to pass as --pid.

* Log auto-detected values a bit more.

entry.title: Don't call PDM::Refresh() after profile modifications.
entry.content:
(This assumes some familiarity with the PDM. See the CL description of

http://crrev.com/c/4862023 and go/pdm-autofill-table-interface for

details)



Currently, whenever all pending profile modifications have finished,

the PDM calls Refresh(). This reloads all data from the database,

including not just the profile(s) that have changed, but also all

credit cards, ibans, etc. This is unnecessary, since as explained in

go/pdm-autofill-table-interface, the PDM updates its local state

in PDM::OnAutofillProfileChanged() whenever a modification has finished.

Thus, by the time Refresh() is called, the PDM's state is (almost)

consistent with the database.



Historically, three reasons for this Refresh() existed:

- The Refresh() was introduced to keep the order of the PDM's profile

consistent with the database, since the reading operation had an

ORDER BY clause. See http://crrev.com/c/1406178.

This was refactored in http://crrev.com/c/4295048.

- Updating the modification date. This was refactored in

http://crrev.com/c/4306759.

- Calling FinalizeAfterImport(): When profiles are read from the

database, FinalizeAfterImport() is called. So if e.g.

PDM::AddProfile() is called with a non-finalized profile, since

Refresh() is called eventually, the profile that ends up in the PDMs

state will be finalized.



The third reason could be resolved by calling FinalizeAfterImport() in

the PDM, before modifications are sent to the database. This is brittle,

because the code would then rely on the fact that writing to the DB

and reading from it are inverse operations.



Instead, this CL changes which profiles the PDM is notified about in

OnAutofillProfileChanged(). An extra read call is added in the

AutofillWebDataBackendImpl, that retrieves the written profile from

the DB. This profile is then attached to the notification sent to the

PDM.



As a result, the Refresh() can be removed (more than compensating for

the additional read).



Bug: 1420547

entry.title: Remove unused items from the RaceNetworkRequest hashmap
entry.content:
When the AutoPreload or the race-network-and-fetch-handler option in the

static routing API is enabled, network requests are dispatched and

URLLoaderFactories are held in a hashmap in ServiceWorkerGlobalScope.

Those are consumed inside the fetch handler when fetch(e.request) is

called. But if the fetch handler doesn't call fetch() e.g. fallback,

those hashmap items does not have a chance to be removed.



This CL changes the hashmap items to be removed when the fetch event

finishes, and the URLLoaderFactory is still not consumed at that time.

This may loose the dedupe capability if fetch() is called later e.g.

setTimeout(() => fetch()), but it makes sense to prioritize keeping the

hashmap small.

entry.title: Use model metadata instead of dictionary file
entry.content:
Instead of loading the dictionary from a file, defined by a Finch

feature, initialize it from the metadata. This CL:

- Changes the interface of the vectorizer, which uses the dictionary

for vectorization. Since initialization can no longer fail, the

factory function is removed in favor of a constructor. And instead of

reading from a file, it simply converts from the proto to its internal

representation

- Uses the model metadata to constructor the vectorizer. Since no IO is

involved anymore, this can now happen synchronously.

- Adapts the unit test to send dummy metadata. The dummy metadata is

constructed by reading from the existing test dictionary file. The

dictionary file changes slightly, since the first to indices of the

metadata are implicitly reserved for padding and unknown word tokens.

They don't need to be part of the file anymore.
